The way public-company mergers and acquisitions generally work is that you =
sign a merger agreement, where the buyer promises to pay some agreed price =
for the target company, and then you have to wait months before the deal cl=
oses and the buyer delivers the money. During this waiting period, the buye=
r and target are doing things like getting a shareholder vote, getting anti=
trust and other regulatory approvals, and finalizing the buyer=E2=80=99s fi=
nancing. Most of the time, mergers are happy events: Everyone is excited fo=
r the deal when they sign the deal, and they remain excited for the deal du=
ring the waiting period, and they are excited to close the deal at the end.=
=C2=A0Sometimes not though. Sometimes the world changes between signing and=
 closing. In particular, sometimes the market crashes between signing and c=
losing, due to inflation or war or bubbles popping or=C2=A0deadly pandemics=
 or what have you. Before the crash, it seemed like a good idea to the buye=
r to pay $100 per share for the target, and it seemed like a good idea for =
the target to accept. After the crash, $100 seems a bit rich. The buyer wou=
ld prefer not to pay that much, and the target =E2=80=94=C2=A0while perhaps=
 sympathetic, in the abstract, to the buyer=E2=80=99s regret =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0will really want that $100. After all, it signed a deal to sell before t=
he crash! Its timing was good! It should get the benefit of that deal.[1]Pu=
blic-company merger agreements are very clear about the allocation of risk =
here, and generally this risk is allocated to the buyer.[2] The buyer has n=
o right to get out of the deal because markets went down. Generally the buy=
er can get out of the deal if there is a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=
=E2=80=9D on the target, but that term is always defined to=C2=A0exclude ef=
fects resulting from =E2=80=9Cgeneral economic, regulatory or political con=
ditions=E2=80=9D or conditions =E2=80=9Cin the financial, credit or securit=
ies markets.=E2=80=9D[3] The risk of the market going down is on the buyer.=
Still if you are the buyer, and the market goes down, you will=C2=A0want to=
 get out of the deal. Or you might still like the=C2=A0deal=C2=A0=E2=80=94=
=C2=A0you might still want to own the target company =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=C2=
=A0regret the price. And you might crack open the merger agreement and ask:=
 Well, okay, we can=E2=80=99t get out of the deal for a market crash, but c=
an we get out for some=C2=A0other=C2=A0reason?We have, for reasons,  talked=
 a  lot  about this question recently. You might naively think that you cou=
ld comb through the =E2=80=9Crepresentations and warranties=E2=80=9D in the=
 merger agreement =E2=80=94=C2=A0factual statements about the target=E2=80=
=99s business that it promises are true =E2=80=94=C2=A0to find one that is =
wrong, and use that as a way out of the deal. After all, if the company tol=
d you that it sold 10,000 widgets last year, and it only sold 9,998, then y=
ou are not getting what you agreed to and you should be able to get out of =
the deal.But in practice merger agreements are not set up that way. If a re=
presentation is wrong, the buyer can generally only get out of the deal if =
it would have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect,=E2=80=9D a very high stan=
dard. Rampant fraud might count; the business being half as valuable as you=
 thought might count; 9,998 widgets instead of 10,000 would not. Merger agr=
eements are designed to=C2=A0prevent=C2=A0a buyer from walking away over so=
me trivial misrepresentation.The=C2=A0more promising approach is to comb th=
rough the =E2=80=9Ccovenants=E2=80=9D in the merger agreement, things that =
the target promises to do between signing and closing. If the target breach=
es a=C2=A0covenant, you can get out of the deal=C2=A0without=C2=A0a materia=
l adverse effect: The company has to live up to its promises. =E2=80=9CAs c=
losing conditions for the merger, representations are qualified by MAE, but=
 covenants by =E2=80=98in all material respects,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D  I had o=
ccasion to write last week.There are two main kinds of covenant:=09The targ=
et promises to do things to get the deal done: solicit the shareholder vote=
, seek regulatory approvals, help out with marketing any buyout debt, give =
the buyer information so it can get ready to run the business, etc.=09The t=
arget promises=C2=A0not=C2=A0to do anything crazy: It has to run its busine=
ss =E2=80=9Cin the ordinary course consistent with past practice,=E2=80=9D[=
4] and it generally agrees to limits on things like new business lines, hir=
ing,=C2=A0executive bonuses, stock issuance, etc. The target has agreed to =
sell itself, so its lame-duck managers are=C2=A0basically in the business o=
f acting as=C2=A0caretakers for its future owners; they can=E2=80=99t make =
any big changes before the new owners show up.In theory you could claim a b=
reach of=C2=A0either one, and nervous buyers=C2=A0do.=C2=A0Back in the spri=
ng of 2020, the Covid-19 pandemic made some buyers regret the deals they ha=
d struck: If you agreed to buy a mall retailer in late 2019, and before the=
 deal closed every mall was shut down for an unknown period of time due to =
a deadly pandemic, you might want to get out of your deal. But =E2=80=9Ca d=
eadly pandemic has ruined the target=E2=80=99s business=E2=80=9D is very, v=
ery, very much the sort of general risk that is allocated to the buyer in a=
 public-company merger, so you can=E2=80=99t. But buyers got creative and r=
ealized that the pandemic could create a=C2=A0covenant breach:=C2=A0The tar=
get certainly could not run its business =E2=80=9Cin the ordinary course co=
nsistent with past practice=E2=80=9D if it was closing all of its stores du=
e to a pandemic, so=C2=A0that could be a way out of the deal. And in fact  =
this happened in Sycamore Partners=E2=80=99 deal to buy Victoria=E2=80=99s =
Secret, and it (somewhat shockingly) worked: The seller let Sycamore out of=
 the deal to avoid going to court over this.It's been a tough few months fo=
r tech stocks, and some number of buyers=C2=A0are regretting their choice t=
o buy tech companies at pre-April-2022 prices. For instance, Sujeet Indap a=
t the Financial Times reports:Thoma Bravo has successfully pressured softwa=
re company Anaplan to cut the $10.7bn price at which it is selling itself t=
o the private equity firm, in one of the largest buyout deals to be renegot=
