Last year Ryan Selkis, the founder of crypto research firm Messari, tweeted=
 that =E2=80=9Ccrypto is Occupy Wall Street but with money and solutions.=
=E2=80=9D Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Joe Weisenthal replied to ask =E2=80=9Cwhat a=
re the solutions,=E2=80=9D and I jumped in to make some jokes. =E2=80=9CAt =
a high enough level,=E2=80=9D I tweeted, =E2=80=9Cthe problem was =E2=80=98=
banks stole my money=E2=80=99 and the solution is =E2=80=98hackers will ste=
al your money instead.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9DWeirdly, I think about this exchang=
e a lot. I agree with Selkis=C2=A0that some of the appeal of crypto comes f=
rom deep suspicion of the traditional banking system in the aftermath of th=
e 2008 financial crisis. Banks were meant to be safe places where people co=
uld put their money, and it turned out that the banks were doing weird risk=
y stuff with that money. The weird risky stuff incurred losses, and those l=
osses were socialized =E2=80=94=C2=A0the government stepped in to bail out =
the banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0in ways that people found surprising and upsetting=
=C2=A0and unfair. One popular reaction to the crisis was to call for banks =
to take fewer risks with depositors=E2=80=99 money, to be safer and less le=
veraged and more transparent. Another popular reaction=C2=A0was to become s=
uspicious of the banking system entirely, and crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0a finan=
cial system that does not rely on banks and that is philosophically less le=
vered than the traditional financial system =E2=80=94=C2=A0helped meet the =
demand for something else.But I also think that often the way crypto works =
in practice is to take the problems of the banking system and=C2=A0make the=
m much=C2=A0worse. If you don=E2=80=99t like the financial system making le=
veraged speculative bets with your deposits, you might find yourself puttin=
g your money in some entirely unregulated crypto bank whose=C2=A0entire pur=
pose=C2=A0is to make leveraged speculative bets with your money. Maybe that=
 will work out great for you? I guess the good news is that if it works out=
 poorly, the losses won=E2=80=99t be socialized in quite the same way they =
were in 2008. The Federal Reserve and the US government are not going to ba=
il out some crypto lending project. You=E2=80=99ll just lose your money.=C2=
=A0Here is Alex Mashinsky, the founder of=C2=A0crypto banking thingy Celsiu=
s Networks LLC, quoted in a  Bloomberg Businessweek article from this Janua=
ry:Mashinsky told Bloomberg Businessweek that Celsius is able to pay such h=
igh yields because it passes along most of its earnings to its users. He sa=
id it=E2=80=99s the traditional financial system that=E2=80=99s ripping peo=
ple off by taking their deposits, using them to make money, and then claimi=
ng it can only pay tiny interest rates. =E2=80=9CSomebody is lying,=E2=80=
=9D Mashinsky said. =E2=80=9CEither the bank is lying or Celsius is lying.=
=E2=80=9DThis schtick works:In testimonials posted last year on Twitter as =
part of a contest in which customers shared their =E2=80=9CCelsius Story,=
=E2=80=9D many said they had entrusted Celsius with their life savings. One=
 said he took out home equity and cashed in his work pension and his saving=
s for his kids=E2=80=99 education to put the money into the company=E2=80=
=99s accounts. Another said it let him quit his job to move closer to his k=
id. One entry read: =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t trust the banking system, but =
I trust #Celsius.=E2=80=9DAs that article explains, the basic idea of Celsi=
us is that you can deposit your cryptocurrencies with Celsius =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0essentially, lend them to Celsius =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it will pay you a p=
retty high interest rate, or an even higher interest rate if you=E2=80=99ll=
 accept payment in its own CEL token. Or you can borrow cryptocurrencies fr=
om Celsius and pay it interest.=C2=A0Think about possible explanations for =
how=C2=A0Celsius could offer a higher interest rate on deposits than your l=
ocal bank:=09The bank is lying.=C2=A0=09Celsius is lying.=09Celsius is maki=
ng=C2=A0riskier loans=C2=A0than your bank, which carry higher interest rate=
s. Functionally, if Celsius is lending out cryptocurrencies, it is lending =
them to crypto speculators who want to make leveraged bets on those currenc=
ies. In particular, if it is lending out Bitcoins or other volatile cryptoc=
urrencies, it is lending them to people who want to short those cryptocurre=
ncies; if it is lending out stablecoins, it is lending them to people who w=
ant to get leveraged=C2=A0long=C2=A0volatile cryptocurrencies. Making lever=
aged speculative bets on volatile assets with limited trading histories=C2=
=A0is=C2=A0riskier=C2=A0than, you know, lending people money to buy houses,=
 and so it carries a higher interest rate, which Celsius can pass on to its=
 depositors. But it also means that those deposits are riskier: If Celsius =
doesn=E2=80=99t get paid back, you are in trouble.=09Much of banking regula=
tion reduces the interest that banks can pass on to its depositors. If a ba=
nk has $100 of deposits and can lend out money at 5%, it can=E2=80=99t just=
 lend out=C2=A0$100 at 5%, collect 0.1% for its trouble and pass on 4.9% to=
 depositors. A bank has=C2=A0capital requirements,=C2=A0meaning that if it =
has $100 of loans it will need to have, say, $10 of equity capital that req=
uires some economic return, reducing the amount that can be passed on to de=
positors. It has=C2=A0liquidity requirements, meaning that if it has $100 o=
f deposits it can=E2=80=99t put them all into long-term loans; it has to ke=
ep some of the money in=C2=A0cash in case any depositors want their money b=
ack. It pays fees to the government for deposit insurance. Prudential regul=
ators examine the bank and make sure its mix of business isn=E2=80=99t too =
risky, which makes it less lucrative.As we know from 2008, there are strong=
 incentives, at a bank,=C2=A0(1) to fund as much of your business as possib=
le with cheap deposits (that is: to be very levered), (2) to put as much mo=
ney as possible into lucrative business rather than keeping it in the cash =
drawer, and (3) to choose risky lucrative businesses over safe boring busin=
esses. But there are=C2=A0constraints=C2=A0on banks=C2=A0to stop them from =
going too far in that direction. One important set of constraints comes fro=
m regulation: Capital and liquidity and prudential regulation prevent banks=
 from gambling too much with depositors=E2=80=99 money. Another important s=
et of constraints comes from transparency and reputation: Banks have to pro=
duce audited financial statements explaining, in some detail, what they are=
 doing with their money; if the stuff they are doing is too weird then they=
=E2=80=99ll have a hard time raising more money. Those constraints are impe=
rfect! 2008 happened! People get mad at banks a lot! Still, the constraints=
