1] Conversely, what if the market soars and the target regrets signing the =
deal at $100 because it is now worth $150? This is a less pressing problem,=
 for various reasons. For one thing, markets =E2=80=9Ctake the stairs up an=
d the elevator down,=E2=80=9D so a rapid market melt-up seems less probable=
 than a rapid meltdown. For another thing, buyouts are generally agreed at =
a premium, so the merger price probably looks good even relative to a risin=
g stock price. But, yes, sometimes it happens that the target thinks =E2=80=
=9Cif we were selling ourselves now we would get $150,=E2=80=9D and the way=
 merger agreements generally handle that is with a negotiated provision abo=
ut when and how the target can accept a =E2=80=9Csuperior offer.=E2=80=9D I=
n most deals, there is a =E2=80=9Cno-shop=E2=80=9D clause prohibiting the t=
arget from *seeking* a better offer, but for fiduciary-duty reasons the tar=
get is generally allowed to *accept* a better offer, if it comes in unsolic=
ited, as long as it gives the buyer a matching right and a breakup fee if i=
t takes the other deal. Also, generally, the target=E2=80=99s shareholders =
can vote down the deal =E2=80=94=C2=A0if, for instance, they decide that th=
e target is now worth $150. So in some rough sense the buyer takes at least=
 some of the risk of the stock market going *up*: If things get vastly bett=
er for the target between signing and closing, the target maybe *can* get o=
ut of the agreed deal.[2] There is an approximate=C2=A0exception in many pr=
ivate-equity-type buyouts where there will be a financing condition where t=
he buyer can get out of the deal if it can=E2=80=99t get financing, but gen=
erally in big modern deals the financing is pretty committed and there is n=
o explicit financing condition.[3] I am quoting from the definition of =E2=
=80=9CCompany Material Adverse Effect=E2=80=9D in the Twitter Inc. merger a=
greement (page A-4 here). The definition of =E2=80=9CMaterial Adverse Effec=
t=E2=80=9D in the Anaplan Inc. merger agreement (page A-6 here) excludes th=
e results of =E2=80=9Cgeneral changes in the economy or securities, credit,=
 financial or other capital markets of the U.S. or any other region outside=
 of the U.S.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0[4] Here I am quoting Section 5.1(a) of the Anap=
lan merger agreement. In Section 6.1 of the Twitter merger agreement, Twitt=
er promises to =E2=80=9Cuse its commercially reasonable efforts to conduct =
the business of the Company and its Subsidiaries in the ordinary course of =
business.=E2=80=9D[5] Indap notes: =E2=80=9CWhile the Anaplan chief later o=
ffered to reduce pay grants to himself and other senior executives, Thoma B=
ravo was unmoved and the firm feared that attempts to =E2=80=98remediate th=
e actions would risk damaging employee morale=E2=80=99.=E2=80=9D That is, i=
f you=E2=80=99re trying to get out of the deal, you have to be able to argu=
e that the covenant breach is somehow unfixable. =E2=80=9CYou told employee=
s you would pay them too much, so we can walk, but if you don=E2=80=99t pay=
 them that much we can also walk.=E2=80=9D[6]=C2=A0Elon Musk has  made simi=
lar threats to Twitter, about how really his=C2=A0banks=C2=A0need more info=
rmation about Twitter=E2=80=99s supposed bot problem.[7] When I say =E2=80=
=9Cmore or less waive,=E2=80=9D I guess I mean what Anaplan got: No conditi=
ons for reps and warranties, and only =E2=80=9Cwillful breach after the ame=
ndment that is material to the transaction=E2=80=9D for covenants. Maybe ev=
en stronger than that; it=E2=80=99s Elon Musk we=E2=80=99re talking about. =
Also I would remove the financing condition to Musk=E2=80=99s specific-perf=
ormance obligation, so that he is just on the hook to fund the whole merger=
 whether or not his banks fund, so he can=E2=80=99t use his banks as an exc=
use.[8]=C2=A0This is kind of a joke, and M&A lawyers tend to believe that t=
here are good reasons for breakup fees to typically be single-digit percent=
ages of deal value. But I actually think that $20 billion is a reasonable e=
stimate of the damages that Twitter would suffer from Musk walking away? I=
=E2=80=99d ask for $20 billion. The point is that you never want the breaku=
p fee, Musk should be required to close the deal in all circumstances, but =
he fights everything so you want your backup to be an enormous fee.
