</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way public-company mergers and acq=
uisitions generally work is that you sign a merger agreement, where the buy=
er promises to pay some agreed price for the target company, and then you h=
ave to wait months before the deal closes and the buyer delivers the money.=
 During this waiting period, the buyer and target are doing things like get=
ting a shareholder vote, getting antitrust and other regulatory approvals, =
and finalizing the buyer=E2=80=99s financing. Most of the time, mergers are=
 happy events: Everyone is excited for the deal when they sign the deal, an=
d they remain excited for the deal during the waiting period, and they are =
excited to close the deal at the end.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Sometimes not though. Sometimes the world changes between signing and clos=
ing. In particular, sometimes the market crashes between signing and closin=
g, due to inflation or war or bubbles popping or=C2=A0deadly pandemics or w=
hat have you. Before the crash, it seemed like a good idea to the buyer to =
pay $100 per share for the target, and it seemed like a good idea for the t=
arget to accept. After the crash, $100 seems a bit rich. The buyer would pr=
efer not to pay that much, and the target =E2=80=94=C2=A0while perhaps symp=
athetic, in the abstract, to the buyer=E2=80=99s regret =E2=80=94=C2=A0will=
 really want that $100. After all, it signed a deal to sell before the cras=
h! Its timing was good! It should get the benefit of that deal.[1]</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Public-company merger agreements are very clear abo=
ut the allocation of risk here, and generally this risk is allocated to the=
 buyer.[2] The buyer has no right to get out of the deal because markets we=
nt down. Generally the buyer can get out of the deal if there is a =E2=80=
=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D on the target, but that term is always =
defined to=C2=A0<em>exclude</em> effects resulting from =E2=80=9Cgeneral ec=
onomic, regulatory or political conditions=E2=80=9D or conditions =E2=80=9C=
in the financial, credit or securities markets.=E2=80=9D[3] The risk of the=
 market going down is on the buyer.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still i=
f you are the buyer, and the market goes down, you will=C2=A0<em>want </em>=
to get out of the deal. Or you might still like the=C2=A0<em>deal=C2=A0</em=
>=E2=80=94=C2=A0you might still want to own the target company =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but=C2=A0regret the <em>price</em>. And you might crack open the merger =
agreement and ask: Well, okay, we can=E2=80=99t get out of the deal for a m=
arket crash, but can we get out for some=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>reason?</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have, for reasons, <a href=3D"https://lin=
