=E2=80=94=C2=A0factual statements about the target=E2=80=99s business that =
it promises are true =E2=80=94=C2=A0to find one that is wrong, and use that=
 as a way out of the deal. After all, if the company told you that it sold =
10,000 widgets last year, and it only sold 9,998, then you are not getting =
what you agreed to and you should be able to get out of the deal.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in practice merger agreements are not set up tha=
t way. If a representation is wrong, the buyer can generally only get out o=
f the deal if it would have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect,=E2=80=9D a =
very high standard. Rampant fraud might count; the business being half as v=
aluable as you thought might count; 9,998 widgets instead of 10,000 would n=
ot. Merger agreements <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
