px 0;">Weirdly, I think about this exchange a lot. I agree with Selkis=C2=
=A0that some of the appeal of crypto comes from deep suspicion of the tradi=
tional banking system in the aftermath of the 2008 financial crisis. Banks =
were meant to be safe places where people could put their money, and it tur=
ned out that the banks were doing weird risky stuff with that money. The we=
ird risky stuff incurred losses, and those losses were socialized =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the government stepped in to bail out the banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0in way=
s that people found surprising and upsetting=C2=A0and unfair. One popular r=
eaction to the crisis was to call for banks to take fewer risks with deposi=
tors=E2=80=99 money, to be safer and less leveraged and more transparent. A=
nother popular reaction=C2=A0was to become suspicious of the banking system=
 entirely, and crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0a financial system that does not rely =
on banks and that is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/28041567.268603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjItMDYtMDEvY3J5cHRvLWNsZWFyaW5nLWFuZC1jcmVkaXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMzIyX01=
PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm=
09MjIwNjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf18a535=
e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">philosophically less levered</a> than the traditional financia=
l system =E2=80=94=C2=A0helped meet the demand for something else.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I also think that often the way crypto works in=
 practice is to take the problems of the banking system and=C2=A0<em>make t=
hem much</em><em>=C2=A0worse</em>. If you don=E2=80=99t like the financial =
system making leveraged speculative bets with your deposits, you might find=
 yourself putting your money in some entirely unregulated crypto bank whose=
=C2=A0<em>entire purpose=C2=A0</em>is to make leveraged speculative bets wi=
th your money. Maybe that will work out great for you? I guess the good new=
s is that if it works out poorly, the losses won=E2=80=99t be socialized in=
 quite the same way they were in 2008. The Federal Reserve and the US gover=
nment are not going to bail out some crypto lending project. You=E2=80=99ll=
 just lose your money.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is Alex M=
ashinsky, the founder of=C2=A0crypto banking thingy Celsius Networks LLC, q=
uoted in a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2804156=
7.268603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMj=
cvY2Vsc2l1cy1zLTE4LXlpZWxkcy1vbi1jcnlwdG8tYXJlLXRlbXB0aW5nLWFuZC1kcmF3aW5nL=
XNjcnV0aW55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MTMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDYxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
mZiN4ajR5N3Z6a2c_c3JlZj0xa0pWTnFuVQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB68faaac7" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;"> Bloomberg Businessweek article</a> from this January:</p><blockquote><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mashinsky told Bloomberg Businessweek that Cels=
ius is able to pay such high yields because it passes along most of its ear=
nings to its users. He said it=E2=80=99s the traditional financial system t=
hat=E2=80=99s ripping people off by taking their deposits, using them to ma=
ke money, and then claiming it can only pay tiny interest rates. =E2=80=9CS=
omebody is lying,=E2=80=9D Mashinsky said. =E2=80=9CEither the bank is lyin=
g or Celsius is lying.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">This schtick works:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In testim=
onials posted last year on Twitter as part of a contest in which customers =
shared their =E2=80=9CCelsius Story,=E2=80=9D many said they had entrusted =
Celsius with their life savings. One said he took out home equity and cashe=
d in his work pension and his savings for his kids=E2=80=99 education to pu=
t the money into the company=E2=80=99s accounts. Another said it let him qu=
it his job to move closer to his kid. One entry read: =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=
=99t trust the banking system, but I trust #Celsius.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As that article explains, the basic idea of=
 Celsius is that you can deposit your cryptocurrencies with Celsius =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0essentially, lend them to Celsius =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it will pay y=
ou a pretty high interest rate, or an even higher interest rate if you=E2=
=80=99ll accept payment in its own CEL token. Or you can borrow cryptocurre=
ncies from Celsius and pay it interest.=C2=A0Think about possible explanati=
ons for how=C2=A0Celsius could offer a higher interest rate on deposits tha=
n your local bank:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: =
40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank is lyi=
ng.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Celsius is lying.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Celsius is making=C2=A0<em>riskier loa=
ns=C2=A0</em>than your bank, which carry higher interest rates. Functionall=
y, if Celsius is lending out cryptocurrencies, it is lending them to crypto=
 speculators who want to make leveraged bets on those currencies. In partic=
ular, if it is lending out Bitcoins or other volatile cryptocurrencies, it =
is lending them to people who want to short those cryptocurrencies; if it i=
s lending out stablecoins, it is lending them to people who want to get lev=
eraged=C2=A0long<em>=C2=A0</em>volatile cryptocurrencies. Making leveraged =
speculative bets on volatile assets with limited trading histories=C2=A0is=
=C2=A0<em>riskier=C2=A0</em>than, you know, lending people money to buy hou=
ses, and so it carries a higher interest rate, which Celsius can pass on to=
 its depositors. But it also means that those deposits are riskier: If Cels=
ius doesn=E2=80=99t get paid back, you are in trouble.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Much of banking regulation reduces the interest that b=
anks can pass on to its depositors. If a bank has $100 of deposits and can =
lend out money at 5%, it can=E2=80=99t just lend out=C2=A0$100 at 5%, colle=
ct 0.1% for its trouble and pass on 4.9% to depositors. A bank has=C2=A0<em=
>capital requirements,=C2=A0</em>meaning that if it has $100 of loans it wi=
ll need to have, say, $10 of equity capital that requires some economic ret=
urn, reducing the amount that can be passed on to depositors. It has=C2=A0<=
em>liquidity requirements</em>, meaning that if it has $100 of deposits it =
can=E2=80=99t put them all into long-term loans; it has to keep some of the=
 money in=C2=A0cash in case any depositors want their money back. It pays f=
ees to the government for deposit insurance. Prudential regulators examine =
the bank and make sure its mix of business isn=E2=80=99t too risky, which m=
akes it less lucrative.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As we know fr=
om 2008, there are strong incentives, at a bank,=C2=A0(1) to fund as much o=
f your business as possible with cheap deposits (that is: to be very levere=
d), (2) to put as much money as possible into lucrative business rather tha=
n keeping it in the cash drawer, and (3) to choose risky lucrative business=
es over safe boring businesses. But there are=C2=A0<em>constraints=C2=A0</e=
m>on banks=C2=A0to stop them from going too far in that direction. One impo=
rtant set of constraints comes from regulation: Capital and liquidity and p=
rudential regulation prevent banks from gambling too much with depositors=
=E2=80=99 money. Another important set of constraints comes from transparen=
cy and reputation: Banks have to produce audited financial statements expla=
ining, in some detail, what they are doing with their money; if the stuff t=
hey are doing is too weird then they=E2=80=99ll have a hard time raising mo=
re money. Those constraints are imperfect! 2008 happened! People get mad at=
 banks a lot! Still, the constraints exist.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>In crypto, oh, you know. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/28041567.268603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9u=
ZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMTMvY3J5cHRvLWxlbmRlci1jZWxzaXVzLWZyZWV6ZXMtd2l=
0aGRyYXdhbHMtZnVlbGluZy1tYXJrZXQtcm91dD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjEzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRi=
Z1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA2MTMmd=
XRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdc6490a1" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 an update on Celsius today</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Celsius Network Ltd., one of the biggest lenders in crypto and a key play=
er in the world of decentralized finance, said late Sunday that it was paus=
ing withdrawals, swaps and transfers following weeks of speculation over it=
s ability to make good on the outsize returns it offered on certain of its =
products, including yields as high as 17%. The move effectively halted a pl=
atform with registered entities across the globe and billions of dollars wo=
